be inside the workspace.
   - tar.gz uses gzip compression; zip uses ZIP_DEFLATED.
   - Directory inputs are walked recursively (zip) or added as tar members (tar.gz).

25. **job_spawn** (background tool launch)
   - Returns synchronously with `{job_id, output_path, status: running}`.
   - Phase restriction on the TARGET tool is enforced AT SPAWN TIME (so spawning execute_hydra during informational is rejected, same as a direct call).
   - Tool output is tee'd to `jobs/<job_id>.log` as it produces - readable mid-flight via fs_read on jobs/<job_id>.log or fs_grep with path=jobs.
   - Inner call runs with output_mode=inline so the log captures full content (no nested offload stubs).

26. **job_status** (non-blocking job query)
   - Includes `tail` (last 40 lines of the log) so you can summarise progress without an extra fs_read.
   - Survives agent restart: reads from `jobs/<id>.meta.json` if the in-memory handle is gone.

27. **job_wait** (bounded blocking wait)
   - Returns the same shape as `job_status` regardless of whether the timeout fired or the job finished.
   - Status still `running` after wait? Either keep waiting or move on - the job continues either way.

28. **job_cancel** (cancel running job)
   - Cancels the underlying asyncio task and waits for it to unwind.
   - No-op if the job has already terminated.

29. **job_list** (project job inventory)
   - Returns rows sorted by `started_at` descending.
   - Augments with on-disk meta files so jobs that survived agent restart still appear (with `interrupted` status).

30. **execute_nuclei** (CVE verification & exploitation)
   - 8000+ YAML templates — verify and exploit CVEs in one step
   - Custom templates at `/opt/nuclei-templates/` are listed in the tool description (check it for available paths)
   - Examples: `-u URL -id CVE-2021-41773 -jsonl` | `-u URL -tags cve,rce -severity critical,high -jsonl`
   - Custom: `-u URL -t /opt/nuclei-templates/http/misconfiguration/springboot/ -jsonl`

31. **execute_curl** (HTTP requests)
   - Make HTTP requests for reachability, headers, banners
   - Do NOT use for vuln probing — use execute_nuclei instead

32. **execute_httpx** (HTTP probing & tech fingerprinting)
   - Fast HTTP prober: status codes, page titles, server headers, tech detection
   - Follows redirects, probes specific paths, supports JSON output
   - Example: `-u http://10.0.0.5 -sc -title -server -td -fr -silent -j`
   - Use INSTEAD of curl when you need structured multi-field HTTP fingerprinting

33. **execute_naabu** (Fast port scanning)
   - Verify open ports or scan targets not yet in graph
   - Example: `-host 10.0.0.5 -p 80,443,8080 -json`

34. **execute_jsluice** (JavaScript static analysis -- passive, local only)
   - Extracts hidden API endpoints, URL paths, query parameters from JS files
   - Finds secrets: AWS keys, API tokens, credentials, private keys
   - **Reads LOCAL files only** -- download JS files first via execute_curl
   - Workflow: `execute_curl -s -o /tmp/app.js http://target/js/app.js` then
     `execute_jsluice "urls --resolve-paths http://target /tmp/app.js"`
   - Subcommands: `urls` (endpoints) | `secrets` (credentials/keys)
   - Output: JSON lines (one finding per line)
   - Use after discovering JS file URLs via query_graph or web crawling

35. **execute_katana** (Web crawling & endpoint discovery)
   - Crawls web targets to discover URLs, endpoints, JS-linked paths, and known files
   - JavaScript parsing (`-jc`) finds endpoints hidden in JS bundles
   - Known-file crawling (`-kf all`) checks robots.txt and sitemap.xml
   - Key flags: `-u URL`, `-d depth`, `-jc` (JS crawl), `-jsonl` (JSON output), `-rl rate-limit`, `-c concurrency`, `-kf all|robotstxt|sitemapxml`, `-ef ext1,ext2` (extension filter)
   - Safe baseline: `-u URL -d 3 -jc -kf robotstxt -c 10 -rl 50 -ef png,jpg,gif,css,woff -silent`
   - Use `-jsonl` for JSON output with status codes, content types, and response metadata
   - For large crawls, save to file: `-o /tmp/kata
